From right triangle $AHP,$ $AH^2 + x^2 = 25.$  From right triangle $BHQ,$ $BH^2 + y^2 = 4.$  Adding these equations, we get
\[AH^2 + BH^2 + x^2 + y^2 = 29.\]By the Extended Law of Sines,
\[2R = \frac{BC}{\sin A}.\]Also, $[ABC] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot AC \cdot BH,$ so
\[AC \cdot BH = 2 [ABC] = 2R \cdot \frac{BC}{2} \cdot \frac{AH}{2} = R \cdot AC \cdot AH.\]Hence, $R = \frac{BH}{\sin B}.$  Then
\begin{align*}
(BP)(PC) - (AQ)(CQ) &= xy - (2 - y)(3 - x) \\
&= xy - (6 - 3x - 2y + xy) \\
&= 3x + 2y - 6.
\end{align*}By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\cos A = \frac{BC^2 + AC^2 - AB^2}{2 \cdot BC \cdot AC} = \frac{7}{10}.\]Then $\sin A = \sqrt{1 - \cos^2 A} = \frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{10}.$

By the Law of Sines on triangle $ABH,$
\[\frac{BH}{\sin B} = 2R = \frac{AC \cdot BH}{AC \cdot \sin A} = \frac{2 [ABC]}{\frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{10} \cdot AC} = \frac{20 [ABC]}{3 AC}.\]Hence,
\[\frac{BH}{AC} = \frac{2}{\frac{3 \sqrt{3}}{10}} \cdot \frac{[ABC]}{AC^2} = \frac{20}{3 \sqrt{3} AC^2} \cdot [ABC].\]Then
\begin{align*}
xy &= AC \cdot (BP)(CQ) \\
&= AC \cdot [(BP)(PC) - (BP - x)(CQ - y)] \\
&= AC \cdot [(BP)(PC) - (3 - x)(2 - y) + xy - 5x + 2y],
\end{align*}so
\[xy - AC \cdot [(BP)(PC) - (3 - x)(2 - y)] = 5x - 2y.\]Thus,
\begin{align*}
3x + 2y - 6 &= xy - (2 - y)(3 - x) \\
&= xy - (6 - 3x - 2y + xy) \\
&= 5x - 2y,
\end{align*}so $x = \frac{8}{3}$ and $y = \frac{7}{3},$ and $(BP)(PC) - (AQ)(CQ) = \boxed{4}.$

Since $BP$ and $CQ$ are altitudes of triangles $BHC$ and $AHC,$ respectively, we have that $(BP)(PC) = (HC)(BP)$ and $(AQ)(QC) = (HC)(CQ).$  Hence, we want to compute $(HC)(BP) - (HC)(CQ) = (HC)(BP - CQ).$

