Let $x = BH$ and $y = CH.$  Then $BP = \frac{2}{x}$ and $CQ = \frac{5}{y},$ so
\[(BP)(PC) - (AQ)(QC) = (HC)(BP - CQ) = (x + y) \left( \frac{2}{x} - \frac{5}{y} \right) = \frac{2y - 5x}{x} \cdot (x + y).\]By the Law of Sines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\frac{x}{\sin C} = \frac{y}{\sin B}.\]Since $\triangle ABC$ is acute, $\sin B > 0$ and $\sin C > 0,$ so $x$ and $y$ have the same sign.  Then
\[\frac{2y - 5x}{x} \cdot (x + y) = \frac{2 \sin B - 5 \sin C}{\sin C} \cdot (x + y).\]By the Law of Sines again,
\[2 \sin B = 2 \cdot \frac{BP}{AC} = \frac{4}{AC} \cdot \sqrt{s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)} = \frac{4}{AC} \cdot \sqrt{s(s - a) \cdot \frac{2K}{a}} = \frac{4}{AC} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{2Ks(s - a)}{a}},\]and
\[5 \sin C = 5 \cdot \frac{CQ}{AC} = \frac{5}{AC} \cdot \sqrt{s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)} = \frac{5}{AC} \cdot \sqrt{s(s - a) \cdot \frac{2K}{a}} = \frac{5}{AC} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{2Ks(s - a)}{a}}.\]Hence,
\[\frac{2 \sin B - 5 \sin C}{\sin C} \cdot (x + y) = \frac{4}{5} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2Ks(s - a)}}{AC} \cdot (x + y).\]By Heron's formula,
\[K = \sqrt{s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)} = \frac{1}{4} \sqrt{(2a^2 + 2b^2 - c^2)(2a^2 + 2c^2 - b^2)(2b^2 + 2c^2 - a^2)},\]so
\begin{align*}
\frac{4}{5} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2Ks(s - a)}}{AC} \cdot (x + y) &= \frac{4}{5} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2Ks(s - a)}}{2K/\sqrt{s(s - a)}} \cdot (x + y) \\
&= \frac{4}{5} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{2s(s - a)}{a}} \cdot (x + y) \\
&= \frac{4}{5} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{2bc}{a}} \cdot (x + y) \\
&= \frac{4}{5} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{2 \cdot 6 \cdot 7}{5}} \cdot (x + y) \\
&= \boxed{\frac{24}{5}}.
\end{align*}

